ervative Party of Canada|Progressive Conservative]] member for [[Halifax\u2014East Hants]], [[Nova Scotia]].\n* [[Charles Wilson Cross]] b. 1872 first elected in 1925 as [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] member for [[Athabaska (electoral district)|Athabaska]], [[Alberta]].\n* [[Guy F. Crossman]] b. 1915   first elected in 1962 as [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] member for [[Kent (New Brunswick electoral district)|Kent]], [[New Brunswick]].\n* [[Thomas Wilson Crothers]] b. 1850 first elected in 1908 as [[Conservative Party of Canada (historical)|Conservative]] member for [[Elgin West]], [[Ontario]].\n* [[Lloyd Roseville Crouse]] b. 1918   first elected in 1957 as [[Progressive Conservative Party of Canada|Progressive Conservative]] member for [[Queens\u2014Lunenburg]], [[Nova Scotia]].\n* [[Darius Crouter]] b. 1827 first elected in 1881 as Independent Liberal member for [[Northumberland East]], [[Ontario]].\n* [[Jean Crowder]] b. 1952   first elected in 2004 as [[New Democratic Party of Canada|New Democratic Party]] member for [[Nanaimo\u2014Cowichan]], [[British Columbia]].\n* [[Sanford Johnston Crowe]] b. 1868 first elected in 1917 as [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] member for [[Burrard (electoral district)|Burrard]], [[British Columbia]].\n* [[George Alexander Cruickshank (Canadian politician)]] b. 1897   first elected in 1940 as [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] member for [[Fraser Valley (electoral district)|Fraser Valley]], [[British Columbia]].\n* [[Robert Cruise (Manitoba politician)|Robert Cruise]] b. 1868 first elected in 1911 as [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] member for [[Dauphin (Manitoba electoral district)|Dauphin]], [[Manitoba]].\n\n== Cu ==\n\n* [[Harold William Culbert]] b. 1944   first elected in 1993 as [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] member for [[Carleton\u2014Charlotte]], [[New Brunswick]].\n* [[John Culbert]] b. 1847 first elected in 1900 as [[Conservative Party of Canada (historical)|Conservative]] member for [[Brockville (electoral district)|Brockville]], [[Ontario]].\n* [[Jack Sydney George Cullen]] b. 1927   first elected in 1968 as [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] member for [[Sarnia (electoral district)|Sarnia]], [[Ontario]].\n* [[Nathan Cullen]] b. 1972 first elected in 2004 as [[New Democratic Party of Canada|New Democratic Party]] member for [[Skeena\u2014Bulkley Valley]], [[British Columbia]].\n* [[Roy Cullen]] b. 1944   first elected in 1996 as [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] member for [[Etobicoke North]], [[Ontario]].\n* [[Arthur Culligan]] b. 1879   first elected in 1925 as [[Conservative Party of Canada (historical)|Conservative]] member for [[Restigouche\u2014Madawaska]], [[New Brunswick]].\n* [[Frederick William Cumberland]] b. 1821 first elected in 1871 as [[Conservative Party of Canada (historical)|Conservative]] member for [[Algoma (electoral district)|Algoma]], [[Ontario]].\n* [[John Martin Cummins]] b. 1942   first elected in 1993 as [[Reform Party of Canada|Reform]] member for [[Delta (electoral district)|Delta]], [[British Columbia]].\n* [[James Cunningham (British Columbia politician)|James Cunningham]] b. 1834 first elected in 1874 as [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] member for [[New Westminster (electoral district)|New Westminster]], [[British Columbia]].\n* [[Robert Cunningham (Canadian politician)|Robert Cunningham]] b. 1836 first elected in 1872 as [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] member for [[Marquette (electoral district)|Marquette]], [[Manitoba]].\n* [[Douglas Cunnington]] b. 1885   first elected in 1939 as [[Conservative Party of Canada (historical)|Conservative]] member for [[Calgary West]], [[Alberta]].\n* [[John Joseph Curran]] b. 1842 first elected in 1882 as [[Conservative Party of Canada (historical)|Conservative]] member for [[Montreal Centre]], [[Quebec]].\n* [[John Allister Currie]] b. 1868 first elected in 1908 as [[Conservative Party of Canada (historical)|Conservative]] member for [[Simcoe North]], [[Ontario]].\n* [[Morley Currie]] b. 1869 first elected in 1908 as [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] member for [[Prince Edward (electoral district)|Prince Edward]], [[Ontario]].\n* [[Joseph Merrill Currier]] b. 1820 first elected in 1867 as [[Liberal-Conservative]] member for [[Ottawa (City of)]], [[Ontario]].\n* [[Lemuel Cushing, Jr.]] b. 1842 first elected in 1874 as [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] member for [[Argenteuil (electoral district)|Argenteuil]], [[Quebec]].\n* [[Edward Octavian Cuthbert]] b. 1826 first elected in 1875 as [[Conservative Party of Canada (historical)|Conservative]] member for [[Berthier (electoral district)|Berthier]], [[Quebec]].\n* [[Robert Barry Cutler]] b. 1810 first elected in 1872 as [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] member for [[Kent (New Brunswick electoral district)|Kent]], [[New Brunswick]].\n* [[Rodger Cuzner]] b. 1955 first elected in 2000 as [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] member for [[Bras d'Or\u2014Cape Breton]], [[Nova Scotia]].\n\n== Cy ==\n\n* [[Alexandre Cyr]] b. 1922 first elected in 1963 as [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] member for [[Gasp\u00e9 (electoral district)|Gasp\u00e9]], [[Quebec]].\n* [[Joseph Ernest Cyr]] b. 1854 first elected in 1904 as [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] member for [[Provencher (electoral district)|Provencher]], [[Manitoba]].\n\n{{CanHOC}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of Members of the House of Commons of Canada by surname|C]]\n", "name_user": "Tassedethe", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 - Repaired 1 link to disambiguation page -(You can help)-Paul Couture", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Members_of_the_Canadian_House_of_Commons_(C)"}
{"title_page": "Louise Sorel", "text_new": "{{lead too short|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Louise Sorel\n| image         = Don_Rickles_and_Louise_Sorel,_1971.jpg\n| caption       = [[Don Rickles]] and Louise Sorel in 1971\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1940|8|6}}\n| birth_place   = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| occupation    = Actress\n| birth_name    = Louise Jacqueline Cohen\n| spouse        = [[Ken Howard]] (1973\u20131975; divorced)<br>[[Herb Edelman]] (1964\u20131970; divorced)\n| years_active  = 1957\u2013present\n}}\n'''Louise Jacqueline Sorel''' (born August 6, 1940) is an American actress. Sorel was born in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1994-11-03/features/9411030157_1_vivian-alamain-louise-sorel-daytime-actors|title=Louise Sorel Battles To Give Her Character Character|work=Chicago Tribune|accessdate=October 27, 2014}}</ref>  She received theatrical training at the [[Neighborhood Playhouse School of the Theatre]] in [[New York City|New York]]. She briefly attended the [[Institut Fran\u00e7ais]]{{clarify|date=June 2012}} abroad. Sorel is [[Jewish]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/eatdrinkremarryc0000howa|url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/eatdrinkremarryc0000howa/page/121 121]|quote=Louise Sorel Jewish.|title=Eat, Drink & Remarry: Confessions of a Serial Wife|first=Margo|last=Howard|date=May 15, 2014|publisher=Harlequin|via=Internet Archive}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=June 2017}}\n=== Career ===\nSorel's early career was on the stage; she spent several years on [[Broadway theater|Broadway]], playing roles in ''[[Take Her, She's Mine]]'' and ''[[Man and Boy (play)|Man and Boy]]''. She appeared in stage productions of ''[[The Lion in Winter]]'' and ''[[The Sign in Sidney Brustein's Window]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibdb.com/person.asp?id=106900|title=IBDb profile|author=The Broadway League|accessdate=October 27, 2014}}</ref>\n\nSorel's first feature film appearance was in the film ''[[The Party's Over (1965 film)|The Party's Over]]'' (1965). She appeared in ''[[Plaza Suite (film)|Plaza Suite]]'' (1971),  ''[[Night Gallery]]'' episode \"[[List of Night Gallery episodes#Season 2 .281971.E2.80.9372.29|Pickman's Model]]\" (1971), ''[[B.S. I Love You]]'' (1971), ''[[Every Little Crook and Nanny]]'' (1972), ''[[The Return of Charlie Chan]]'' (1973), ''[[Airplane II: The Sequel]]'' (1982), ''[[Mazes and Monsters]]'' (1982), ''[[Where the Boys Are '84]]'' (1984), and ''[[Crimes of Passion (1984 film)|Crimes of Passion]]'' (1984) among others. She has made guest appearances on more than 50 prime time programs and TV movies, making a guest appearance on ''[[Star Trek: The Original Series|Star Trek]]'' (as \"Rayna\" the android, in the episode \"[[Requiem for Methuselah]]\", which aired in 1969). She also portrayed Terry Waverly, the sister-in-law of Dr. Richard Kimble in an episode of ''[[The Fugitive (TV series)|The Fugitive]]'' in 1965.\n\nShe made other guest appearances on such programs as ''[[Bonanza]]'' (as Marie in the episode \"The Strange One\", 1965), ''[[Daniel Boone (1964 TV series)|Daniel Boone]]'', ''[[The Virginian (TV series)|The Virginian]]'', ''[[Route 66 (TV series)|Route 66]]'', ''[[The Big Valley]]'', ''[[The Fugitive (TV series)|The Fugitive]]'', ''[[Star Trek (TV series)|Star Trek]]'', ''[[Search (TV series)|Search]]'' (as Magda Reiner, in \"Live Men Tell Tales\"), ''[[Vega$]]'', ''[[Hart to Hart]]'', ''[[Medical Center (TV series)|Medical Center]]'', ''[[Charlie's Angels]]'', ''[[Incredible Hulk (TV series)|Hulk]]'', ''[[Hawaii Five-O (1968 TV series)|Hawaii Five-O]]'', ''[[Night Gallery]]'', ''[[The Eddie Capra Mysteries]]'', ''[[Knots Landing]]'', and ''[[Sabrina the Teenage Witch (1996 TV series)|Sabrina the Teenage Witch]]'', among others. She had a principal role on ''[[Don Rickles#Filmography|The Don Rickles Show]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://movies2.nytimes.com/gst/movies/filmography.html?p_id=66923|title=Louise Sorel filmography at ''New York Times''}}</ref> Sorel played Helena Varga, a young woman from a disadvantaged background whose photographic memory becomes valuable to a drug kingpin in the [[David L. Wolper]]-produced TV movie ''[[Get Christie Love]]'' (1974), starring [[Teresa Graves]]. Sorel played Eleanor Greeley in the ''[[Magnum, P.I.]]'' episode \"One More Summer\" (1982).\n\nHer first daytime dramatic role was as eccentric, meddlesome [[Augusta Wainwright]] on the [[NBC]] daytime drama ''[[Santa Barbara (TV series)|Santa Barbara]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.welovesoaps.net/2009/08/interview-lunch-with-louise-sorel-part_11.html|title=Sorel's daytime television career|author=Damon L. Jacobs|accessdate=October 27, 2014}}</ref> She appeared on ''Santa Barbara'' from July 1984 to August 1986, then from November 1988 to May 1989, returning the following October. She remained until October 1991.\n\nIn between stints, she also spent a year appearing as strong-willed but decent District Attorney [[Judith Russell (One Life to Live)|Judith Russell Sanders]] on the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] soap opera ''[[One Life to Live]]'', from August 1986 through November 1987. She played the villainous [[Vivian Alamain]] on the [[NBC]] daytime serial, ''[[Days of Our Lives]]'' from March 1992 until February 2000. Sorel's performance as Alamain garnered her five [[Soap Opera Digest Awards]] as \"Outstanding Villainess\" in 1994, \"Outstanding Showstopper\" in 1997 and again in 1999 as \"Outstanding Scene Stealer\".\n\nIn 2000, shortly after being let go from ''[[Days of Our Lives]]'', Sorel briefly joined the cast of the ''[[Port Charles]]'' as fashion maven \"Donatella Stewart\" (a play on the names [[Donatella Versace]] and [[Martha Stewart]]). The role lasted for a month. In 2001, she had a brief role on another [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] soap opera ''[[All My Children]]'' as \"Judge Kay Campobello\" who blackmailed [[Adam Chandler]] into sleeping with her. She made a brief appearance on ''[[Passions]]'' as cannery worker [[Minor Passions characters#Dort|Dort]] in 2004. In December 2009, she was invited to reprise her villainous role on ''Days of Our Lives''.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nIn June 2011, Sorel was let go from ''Days of Our Lives'' along with many other actors to make room for the return of supercouple John and Marlena and several other characters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvline.com/2011/06/days-of-our-lives-hogestyn-hall-sorel-chappell//|title=Days of Our Lives Shake-Up! Hogestyn and Hall Return, Sorel and Chappell Out|work=TVLine|accessdate=October 27, 2014}}</ref> In 2014, Sorel played Emily Tanner in the soap opera [[web series]] ''[[Beacon Hill (web series)|Beacon Hill]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abc.soapsindepth.com/2014/02/a-whos-who-guide-for-beacon-hill.html|title=A Who's Who Guide For ''Beacon Hill''!|work=[[ABC Soaps In Depth]]|date=February 28, 2014|accessdate=September 26, 2015 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905194216/http://abc.soapsindepth.com/2014/02/a-whos-who-guide-for-beacon-hill.html|archivedate=September 5, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://beaconhilltheseries.com/characters.html|title=The Characters|publisher=Beaconhilltheseries.com|accessdate=September 27, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150811115357/http://beaconhilltheseries.com/characters.html|archive-date=August 11, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn December 29, 2017, Sorel returned to ''Days of Our Lives'' as Vivian. However, she was briefly replaced by [[Robin Strasser]]. On December 30, 2019, it was announced that Sorel would once again return to the role in 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://soapdirt.com/days-of-our-lives-spoilers-vivian-back-with-stefan-louise-sorel-return-hinted/|title=Louise Sorel Returns as Vivian to Days|date=2019-12-30|access-date=2019-12-30|website=Soap Dirt|archive-url=https://archive.today/20191230181309/https://soapdirt.com/days-of-our-lives-spoilers-vivian-back-with-stefan-louise-sorel-return-hinted/|archive-date=2019-12-30|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n* 2014\u2013present: ''[[Beacon Hill (web series)|Beacon Hill]]'' \u2013 Emily Tanner\n* 1992\u20132018: ''[[Days of Our Lives]]'' \u2013 Vivian Alamain\n* 2004: ''[[Passions]]'' \u2013 Dort\n* 1998: ''[[Sabrina the Teenage Witch (TV series)|Sabrina the Teenage Witch]]'' \u2013 Mrs. Saberhagen\n* 1996: ''[[Law & Order]]'' \u2013 Marcy Fletcher Wrightman\n* 1984\u20131991: ''[[Santa Barbara (TV series)|Santa Barbara]]'' \u2013 Augusta Lockridge\n* 1986: ''[[One Life to Live]]'' \u2013 Judith Sanders\n* 1983: ''[[Diff'rent Strokes]]'' \u2013 Robin Saunders\n* 1982: ''[[Airplane II: The Sequel]]'' \u2013 Nurse\n* 1982: ''[[Knots Landing]]'' \u2013 Bess Riker\n* 1982: ''[[Trapper John, M.D.]]'' \u2013 Marty Katz\n* 1982: ''[[Magnum, P.I.]]'' \u2013 Eleanor Greeley\n* 1977: ''[[Kojak]]'' \u2013 Janice Maclay\n* 1972: ''[[The Don Rickles Show]]'' \u2013 Barbara Robinson\n* 1969: ''[[Star Trek: The Original Series]]'' \u2013 Rayna\n* 1968: ''[[Mannix S1Ep22 ''Delayed Reaction'']]'' \u2013 Danielle Michaels / Merry Higgins\n* 1965: ''[[Bonanza]]'' \u2013 Marie\n\n== Awards ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Year\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Award\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Category\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Work\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Result\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[List of Soap Opera Digest Awards|3rd Soap Opera Digest Award]]''\n|  Outstanding Comic Relief Role on a Daytime Serial\n| ''[[Santa Barbara (TV series)|Santa Barbara]]''\n| {{Nom }}\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''3rd Soap Opera Digest Award''\n| Outstanding Actress in a Supporting Role on a Daytime Serial\n| ''Santa Barbara''\n| {{Nom }}\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''[[List of Soap Opera Digest Awards|9th Soap Opera Digest Award]