 birth_name    = Louise Jacqueline Cohen\n| spouse        = [[Ken Howard]] (1973\u20131975; divorced)<br>[[Herb Edelman]] (1964\u20131970; divorced)\n| years_active  = 1957\u2013present\n}}\n'''Louise Jacqueline Sorel''' (born August 6, 1940) is an American actress. Sorel was born in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1994-11-03/features/9411030157_1_vivian-alamain-louise-sorel-daytime-actors|title=Louise Sorel Battles To Give Her Character Character|work=Chicago Tribune|accessdate=October 27, 2014}}</ref>  She received theatrical training at the [[Neighborhood Playhouse School of the Theatre]] in [[New York City|New York]]. She briefly attended the [[Institut Fran\u00e7ais]]{{clarify|date=June 2012}} abroad. Sorel is [[Jewish]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/eatdrinkremarryc0000howa|url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/eatdrinkremarryc0000howa/page/121 121]|quote=Louise Sorel Jewish.|title=Eat, Drink & Remarry: Confessions of a Serial Wife|first=Margo|last=Howard|date=May 15, 2014|publisher=Harlequin|via=Internet Archive}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=June 2017}}\n=== Career ===\nSorel's early career was on the stage; she spent several years on [[Broadway theater|Broadway]], playing roles in ''[[Take Her, She's Mine]]'' and ''[[Man and Boy (play)|Man and Boy]]''. She appeared in stage productions of ''[[The Lion in Winter]]'' and ''[[The Sign in Sidney Brustein's Window]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibdb.com/person.asp?id=106900|title=IBDb profile|author=The Broadway League|accessdate=October 27, 2014}}</ref>\n\nSorel's first feature film appearance was in the film ''[[The Party's Over (1965 film)|The Party's Over]]'' (1965). She appeared in ''[[Plaza Suite (film)|Plaza Suite]]'' (1971),  ''[[Night Gallery]]'' episode \"[[List of Night Gallery episodes#Season 2 .281971.E2.80.9372.29|Pickman's Model]]\" (1971), ''[[B.S. I Love You]]'' (1971), ''[[Every Little Crook and Nanny]]'' (1972), ''[[The Return of Charlie Chan]]'' (1973), ''[[Airplane II: The Sequel]]'' (1982), ''[[Mazes and Monsters]]'' (1982), ''[[Where the Boys Are '84]]'' (1984), and ''[[Crimes of Passion (1984 film)|Crimes of Passion]]'' (1984) among others. She has made guest appearances on more than 50 prime time programs and TV movies, making a guest appearance on ''[[Star Trek: The Original Series|Star Trek]]'' (as \"Rayna\" the android, in the episode \"[[Requiem for Methuselah]]\", which aired in 1969). She also portrayed Terry Waverly, the sister-in-law of Dr. Richard Kimble in an episode of ''[[The Fugitive (TV series)|The Fugitive]]'' in 1965.\n\nShe made other guest appearances on such programs as ''[[Bonanza]]'' (as Marie in the episode \"The Strange One\", 1965), ''[[Daniel Boone (1964 TV series)|Daniel Boone]]'', ''[[The Virginian (TV series)|The Virginian]]'', ''[[Route 66 (TV series)|Route 66]]'', ''[[The Big Valley]]'', ''[[The Fugitive (TV series)|The Fugitive]]'', ''[[Star Trek (TV series)|Star Trek]]'', ''[[Search (TV series)|Search]]'' (as Magda Reiner, in \"Live Men Tell Tales\"), ''[[Vega$]]'', ''[[Hart to Hart]]'', ''[[Medical Center (TV series)|Medical Center]]'', ''[[Charlie's Angels]]'', ''[[Incredible Hulk (TV series)|Hulk]]'', ''[[Hawaii Five-O (1968 TV series)|Hawaii Five-O]]'', ''[[Night Gallery]]'', ''[[The Eddie Capra Mysteries]]'', ''[[Knots Landing]]'', and ''[[Sabrina the Teenage Witch (1996 TV series)|Sabrina the Teenage Witch]]'', among others. She had a principal role on ''[[Don Rickles#Filmography|The Don Rickles Show]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://movies2.nytimes.com/gst/movies/filmography.html?p_id=66923|title=Louise Sorel filmography at ''New York Times''}}</ref> Sorel played Helena Varga, a young woman from a disadvantaged background whose photographic memory becomes valuable to a drug kingpin in the [[David L. Wolper]]-produced TV movie ''[[Get Christie Love]]'' (1974), starring [[Teresa Graves]]. Sorel played Eleanor Greeley in the ''[[Magnum, P.I.]]'' episode \"One More Summer\" (1982).\n\nHer first daytime dramatic role was as eccentric, meddlesome [[Augusta Wainwright]] on the [[NBC]] daytime drama ''[[Santa Barbara (TV series)|Santa Barbara]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.welovesoaps.net/2009/08/interview-lunch-with-louise-sorel-part_11.html|title=Sorel's daytime television career|author=Damon L. Jacobs|accessdate=October 27, 2014}}</ref> She appeared on ''Santa Barbara'' from July 1984 to August 1986, then from November 1988 to May 1989, returning the following October. She remained until October 1991.\n\nIn between stints, she also spent a year appearing as strong-willed but decent District Attorney [[Judith Russell (One Life to Live)|Judith Russell Sanders]] on the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] soap opera ''[[One Life to Live]]'', from August 1986 through November 1987. She played the villainous [[Vivian Alamain]] on the [[NBC]] daytime serial, ''[[Days of Our Lives]]'' from March 1992 until February 2000. Sorel's performance as Alamain garnered her five [[Soap Opera Digest Awards]] as \"Outstanding Villainess\" in 1994, \"Outstanding Showstopper\" in 1997 and again in 1999 as \"Outstanding Scene Stealer\".\n\nIn 2000, shortly after being let go from ''[[Days of Our Lives]]'', Sorel briefly joined the cast of the ''[[Port Charles]]'' as fashion maven \"Donatella Stewart\" (a play on the names [[Donatella Versace]] and [[Martha Stewart]]). The role lasted for a month. In 2001, she had a brief role on another [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] soap opera ''[[All My Children]]'' as \"Judge Kay Campobello\" who blackmailed [[Adam Chandler]] into sleeping with her. She made a brief appearance on ''[[Passions]]'' as cannery worker [[Minor Passions characters#Dort|Dort]] in 2004. In December 2009, she was invited to reprise her villainous role on ''Days of Our Lives''.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nIn June 2011, Sorel was let go from ''Days of Our Lives'' along with many other actors to make room for the return of supercouple John and Marlena and several other characters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvline.com/2011/06/days-of-our-lives-hogestyn-hall-sorel-chappell//|title=Days of Our Lives Shake-Up! Hogestyn and Hall Return, Sorel and Chappell Out|work=TVLine|accessdate=October 27, 2014}}</ref> In 2014, Sorel played Emily Tanner in the soap opera [[web series]] ''[[Beacon Hill (web series)|Beacon Hill]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abc.soapsindepth.com/2014/02/a-whos-who-guide-for-beacon-hill.html|title=A Who's Who Guide For ''Beacon Hill''!|work=[[ABC Soaps In Depth]]|date=February 28, 2014|accessdate=September 26, 2015 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905194216/http://abc.soapsindepth.com/2014/02/a-whos-who-guide-for-beacon-hill.html|archivedate=September 5, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://beaconhilltheseries.com/characters.html|title=The Characters|publisher=Beaconhilltheseries.com|accessdate=September 27, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150811115357/http://beaconhilltheseries.com/characters.html|archive-date=August 11, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn December 29, 2017, Sorel returned to ''Days of Our Lives'' as Vivian. However, she was briefly replaced by [[Robin Strasser]]. On December 30, 2019, it was announced that Sorel would once again return to the role in 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://soapdirt.com/days-of-our-lives-spoilers-vivian-back-with-stefan-louise-sorel-return-hinted/|title=Louise Sorel Returns as Vivian to Days|date=2019-12-30|access-date=2019-12-30|website=Soap Dirt|archive-url=https://archive.today/20191230181309/https://soapdirt.com/days-of-our-lives-spoilers-vivian-back-with-stefan-louise-sorel-return-hinted/|archive-date=2019-12-30|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n* 2014\u2013present: ''[[Beacon Hill (web series)|Beacon Hill]]'' \u2013 Emily Tanner\n* 1992\u20132018: ''[[Days of Our Lives]]'' \u2013 Vivian Alamain\n* 2004: ''[[Passions]]'' \u2013 Dort\n* 1998: ''[[Sabrina the Teenage Witch (TV series)|Sabrina the Teenage Witch]]'' \u2013 Mrs. Saberhagen\n* 1996: ''[[Law & Order]]'' \u2013 Marcy Fletcher Wrightman\n* 1984\u20131991: ''[[Santa Barbara (TV series)|Santa Barbara]]'' \u2013 Augusta Lockridge\n* 1986: ''[[One Life to Live]]'' \u2013 Judith Sanders\n* 1983: ''[[Diff'rent Strokes]]'' \u2013 Robin Saunders\n* 1982: ''[[Airplane II: The Sequel]]'' \u2013 Nurse\n* 1982: ''[[Knots Landing]]'' \u2013 Bess Riker\n* 1982: ''[[Trapper John, M.D.]]'' \u2013 Marty Katz\n* 1982: ''[[Magnum, P.I.]]'' \u2013 Eleanor Greeley\n* 1977: ''[[Kojak]]'' \u2013 Janice Maclay\n* 1972: ''[[The Don Rickles Show]]'' \u2013 Barbara Robinson\n* 1969: ''[[Star Trek: The Original Series]]'' \u2013 Rayna\n* 1968: ''[[Mannix]]'' \u2013 Danielle Michaels\n* 1965: ''[[Bonanza]]'' \u2013 Marie\n\n== Awards ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Year\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Award\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Category\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Work\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Result\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[List of Soap Opera Digest Awards|3rd Soap Opera Digest Award]]''\n|  Outstanding Comic Relief Role on a Daytime Serial\n| ''[[Santa Barbara (TV series)|Santa Barbara]]''\n| {{Nom }}\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''3rd Soap Opera Digest Award''\n| Outstanding Actress in a Supporting Role on a Daytime Serial\n| ''Santa Barbara''\n| {{Nom }}\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''[[List of Soap Opera Digest Awards|9th Soap Opera Digest Award]]''\n| Outstanding Villain/Villainess\n| ''[[Days of Our Lives]]''\n| {{Nom }}\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''[[List of Soap Opera Digest Awards|10th Soap Opera Digest Award]]''\n| Outstanding Villain/Villainess\n| ''Days of our Lives''\n| {{Won }}\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''[[List of Soap Opera Digest Awards|11th Soap Opera Digest Award]]''\n| Outstanding Female Scene Stealer\n| ''Days of our Lives''\n| {{Won }}\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[List of Soap Opera Digest Awards|12th Soap Opera Digest Award]]''\n| Outstanding Actress in a Supporting Role\n| ''Days of our Lives''\n| {{Won }}\n|-\n| 1997\n| ''[[List of Soap Opera Digest Awards|13th Soap Opera Digest Award]]''\n| Outstanding Female Showstopper\n| ''Days of our Lives''\n| {{Won }}\n|-\n| 1999\n| ''[[List of Soap Opera Digest Awards|15th Soap Opera Digest Award]]''\n| Outstanding Female Scene Stealer\n| ''Days of our Lives''\n| {{Won }}\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{IMDb name|id=0814798}}\n*{{IBDB name}}\n* {{iobdb name|18829}}\n*[http://www.thespectrum.com/story/entertainment/2017/05/09/louise-sorel-star-trek-and-beyond/314240001/  Louise Sorel interview, The Spectrum, Accessed May 16, 2017.]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sorel, Louise}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American soap opera actresses]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Jewish American actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n", "name_user": "Nounours18200", "label": "safe", "comment": "Add detail on her appearance in Mannix TV serie", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Louise_Sorel"}
{"title_page": "Henrik Stenson", "text_new": "{{short description|Swedish professional golfer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox golfer\n| name              = Henrik Stenson\n| image             = Henrik Stenson in Jan 2014.jpg\n| imagesize         = 200px\n| caption           = Stenson at [[Svenska idrottsgalan]] 2014\n| fullname          = Henrik Olof Stenson\n| nickname          =\n| birth_date        = {{birth date and age|1976|4|5|df=y}}\n| birth_place       = [[Gothenburg]], Sweden\n| death_date        = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|1976|4|5|df=y}} -->\n| death_place       =\n| height            = {{height|ft=6|in=2}}\n| weight            = {{convert|190|lb|kg st|abbr=on}}\n| nationality       = {{SWE}}\n| residence         = [[Orlando, Florida]], U.S.\n| spouse            = {{marriage|Emma L\u00f6fgren|2007}}\n| partner           =\n| children          = Lisa, Karl, Alice\n| college           =\n| yearpro           = 1998\n| retired           = <!-- Year retired -->\n| tour              = [[PGA Tour]] (joined 2007)<br>[[European Tour]] (joined 2001)\n| extour            = <!-- Former tours which a member of -->\n| prowins           = 21\n| pgawins           = 6\n| eurowins          = 11\n| japwins           = <!-- Number of Japan Golf Tour wins -->\n| asiawins          = 1\n| sunwins           = 2\n| auswins           = <!-- Number of PGA Tour of Australasia wins -->\n| nwidewins         = <!-- Number of Nationwide Tour wins -->\n| chalwins          = 3\n| champwins         = <!-- Number of Champions Tour wins -->\n| seneurowins       = <!-- Number of European Seniors Tour wins -->\n| otherwins         = 2\n| majorwins         = 1\n| masters           = T5: [[2018 Masters Tournament|2018]]\n| usopen            = T4: [[2014 U.S. Open (golf)|2014]]\n| open              = '''Won''': [[2016 Open Championship|2016]]\n| pga               = 3rd/T3: [[2013 PGA Championship|2013]], [[2014 PGA Championship|2014]]\n| wghofid           = <!-- World Golf Hall of Fame member ID -->\n| wghofyear         = <!-- World Golf Hall of Fame year inducted -->\n| award1            = [[Challenge Tour#Challenge Tour Rankings winners|Challenge Tour<br>Rankings winner]]\n| year1             = 2000\n| award2            = [[FedEx Cup|FedEx Cup Champion]]\n| year2             = [[2013 FedEx Cup Playoffs|2013]]\n| award3            = [[Race to Dubai|Race to Dubai Champion]]\n| year3             = 2013, 2016\n| award4            = [[European Tour Golfer of the Year|European Tour<br>Golfer of the Year]]\n| year4             = 2013, 2016\n| awardssection     = <!-- location of awards page or section -->\n|award5=[[Swedish Golfer of the Year]]|year5=2006, 2007, 2013, 2014, 2016}}\n{{MedalBox|medals=\n{{MedalCountry | {{SWE}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Golf at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2016 Summer Olympics|2016 Rio de Janeiro]]|[[Golf at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's individual|Golf]]}}\n}}\n'''Henrik Olof Stenson'''<ref>{{cite news |title=Historisk vinst av golfaren Henrik Olof Stenson |url=http://sverigesradio.se/sida/artikel.aspx?programid=4916&artikel=6477489 |website=[[Sveriges Radio]] |date=18 July 2016 |accessdate=18 July 2016 |language=Swedish}}</ref> ({{IPA-sv|\u02c8h\u025b\u030cn\u02d0r\u026ak \u02c8st\u011b\u02d0ns\u0254n|pron}}; born 5 April 1976) is a [[Sweden|Swedish]] [[professional golfer]] who plays both on the [[PGA Tour|PGA]] and [[European Tour]]s.\n\nHe is the first male Swedish and first male [[Nordic countries|Nordic]] major champion, having won the [[2016 Open Championship]] at [[Royal Troon]] with a major championship record score of 264. His list of wins also includes some of the other most prestigious tournaments around the world; [[The Players Championship]], [[2007 WGC-Accenture Match Play Championship|WGC-Accenture Match Play Championship]], the [[World Cup (men's golf)|World Cup]], the [[Tour Championship]],  the [[DP World Tour Championship, Dubai]], the [[South African Open (golf)|South African Open]] and [[Nedbank Golf Challenge]].\n\nA two-time [[PGA European Tour|European Tour]] Golfer of the Year ([[2013 European Tour|2013]] and [[2016 European Tour|2016]]), he has spent [[List of male golfers who have been in the world top 10|over 300 weeks ranked in the top ten of the Official World Golf Ranking]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.owgr.com/Ranking/PlayerProfile.aspx?playerID=5994|title=Official World Golf Ranking for Henrik Stenson|website=Official World Golf Ranking|publisher=Official World Golf Ranking|accessdate=17 July 2016}}</ref> and his career high [[Official World Golf Ranking|world ranking]] of second is the best by any male Swedish golfer.\n\nIn 2013, Stenson won the U.S. PGA Tour's [[FedEx Cup]] and the European Tour's [[Race to Dubai]], thus becoming the first player to win both and to win the season finales of both tours.<ref name=ET-Stenson01>{{cite news |title=With this Win: Henrik Stenson \u2013 DP World Tour Champion |url=http://www.europeantour.com/europeantour/season=2013/tournamentid=2013090/news/newsid=212679.html |publisher=[[PGA European Tour]] |date=17 November 2013 |accessdate=17 November 2013 |quote=(Stenson) becomes the first player to win the FedEx Cup Series on the US PGA Tour and The Race to Dubai and in the same season.}}</ref><ref name=GulfNews01>{{cite news |title=Donald and McIlroy praise Stenson's efforts \u2013 Pair impressed with Swede's success on both sides of the Atlantic |publisher=GulfNews.com |url=http://gulfnews.com/sport/golf/donald-and-mcilroy-praise-stenson-s-efforts-1.1256251 |date=17 November 2013 |accessdate=17 November 2013 |first=Ashley |last=Hammond |quote=Although Stenson has not quite replicated the same feat as [[Luke Donald|Donald]] and [[Rory McIlroy|McIlroy]], who achieved respective money list double acts in 2011 and 2012, Stenson is still the first golfer to win both play-off finales on the two tours. On the European Tour, the Race to Dubai is the money list, but in America the money list and season-ending FedExCup are separate, with [[Tiger Woods]] winning the PGA Tour money list this year. Donald said: \"He has not won the money list in the US but he did win the Race to Dubai and the FedExCup, which neither Rory or myself did. Obviously that's very, very impressive. ...\" }}</ref> <ref name=ET-Stenson02>{{cite news |title=Red-hot Stenson resets goals |url=http://www.europeantour.com/europeantour/season=2013/tournamentid=2013090/news/newsid=212770.html |publisher=[[PGA European Tour]] |date=18 November 2013 |accessdate=21 November 2013 |quote=...after securing an historic double ... Stenson became the first man to win The European Tour's Race to Dubai and FedEx Cup on the US PGA Tour in the same year.}}</ref><ref name=OWGR-StensonNov2013>{{cite news |title=Week 46 \u2013 Wins For World No 2 And 3 |url=http://www.officialworldgolfranking.com/news/default.sps?iCategoryID=0&itype=&sNewsMonth=November&sNewsYear=2013&sNewsToMonth=November&sNewsToYear=2013 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20131121093449/http://www.officialworldgolfranking.com/news/default.sps?iCategoryID=0&itype=&sNewsMonth=November&sNewsYear=2013&sNewsToMonth=November&sNewsToYear=2013 |url-status=dead |archive-date=21 November 2013 |publisher=[[Official World Golf Ranking]] |date=18 November 2013 |accessdate=21 November 2013 |quote=Henrik Stenson hailed a \"dream season\" as he claimed a historic double }}</ref><ref name=TheNational01>{{cite news |title=Henrik Stenson overpowers Earth Course and field to double his pleasure |newspaper=[[The National (Abu Dhabi)|The National]] |url=http://www.thenational.ae/sport/golf/henrik-stenson-overpowers-earth-course-and-field-to-double-his-pleasure |date=17 November 2013 |accessdate=19 November 2013 |first=Steve |last=Elling |quote=A month after winning the FedEx Cup points title in Atlanta, Stenson breezed to the European Tour's Race to Dubai points title, too, pocketing a combined US$11&nbsp;million in bonus money and becoming the first member of both circuits to win the seasonal points crowns in the same year. He won the season finales on both tours in the process. \"The double-double,\" Stenson said. \"That's going to take some beating in the future.\"}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nStenson was born in [[Gothenburg]]. At age 11, he had his first golf lesson with local pro Richard Bayliss at Gullbringa Gullbringa Golf & Country Club, in Kung\u00e4lv, north of Gothenburg in September 1988. With parents not playing golf at the time, he first tried the game after following a friend to the course. A natural [[left-hander]], Stenson learned to play golf right-handed.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Warters |first1=Bob |title=Stenson signs to play Srixon clubs and balls |url=http://www.golfmagic.com/equipment-news/stenson-signs-to-play-srixon-clubs-and-balls/4942.html |publisher=Golfmagic.com |accessdate=20 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Stenson|first1=Henrik|title=About Henrik|url=http://www.henrikstenson.com/about-henrik/q-as/?page=4 |website=henrikstenson.com |accessdate=20 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Hopkins|first1=John|title=Stenson's Coronation|url=http://www.globalgolfpost.com/blog/stensons-coronation/|archive-url=https://archive.today/20140820045022/http://www.globalgolfpost.com/blog/stensons-coronation/|url-status=dead|archive-date=20 August 2014|website=globalgolfpost.com|accessdate=20 August 2014}}</ref> In 1991, he moved with his parents to Bj\u00e4rred outside [[Malm\u00f6]] in southern Sweden and became a member of [[Barseb\u00e4ck Golf & Country Club]].<ref>[https://www.aftonbladet.se/sportbladet/a/zLkwX4/barseback-stolta-sager-inte-nej-till-en-staty Barseb\u00e4ck stolta] (in Swedish) ''Aftonbladet'' 18 July 2016</ref> He reached [[Handicap (golf)|handicap]] 5 at age 15, scratch at 18 and played in junior and amateur tournaments in Sweden in his teen years . He represented Sweden at boys and youths levels and in the national amateur team 1994-1998.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Stenson |first1=Henrik |title=My Story Up to the European Tour |url=http://www.henrikstenson.com/about-henrik/my-story/ |website=Henrikstenson.com |accessdate=20 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.http://www.e-magin.se/paper/859d1981/popup/1#/paper/859d1981/46 |magazine=Svensk Golf |title=Sagan om hur Kung Henrik blev den f\u00f6rste |date=August 2016 |pages=44-49}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n\n===1999\u20132012===\nStenson turned professional in 1998 and the following year topped the money rankings on the second tier golf tour in [[Europe]], the [[Challenge Tour]]. He joined the main [[European Tour]] in 2001, and that year, he won the [[Benson & Hedges International Open]] for his first European Tour victory. Each year from 2005 to 2008, he finished in the top 10 of the [[European Order of Merit|European Tour Order of Merit]].\n\nStenson reached the top 20 of the [[Official World Golf Ranking]] in 2006 and the top 10 in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialworldgolfranking.com/news/fullstory.sps?iNewsid=401070&itype=&iCategoryID=0 |title=Week 5 \u2013 Aaron Baddeley Wins The FBR Open And Breaks Into The World Top 50 \u2013 Henrik Stenson Reaches World Number 10 With Victory At The Dubai Desert Classic |publisher=Official World Golf Ranking |date=5 February 2007 |accessdate=19 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120206052906/http://www.officialworldgolfranking.com/news/fullstory.sps?iNewsid=401070&itype=&iCategoryID=0 |archivedate=6 February 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> In February 2007, Stenson became the first Swede to win one of the [[World Golf Championships]] when he beat [[Geoff Ogilvy]] 2&1 in the final of the [[WGC-Accenture Match Play Championship]]. This victory took Stenson to the top of the [[European Order of Merit]] and to fifth in the world rankings, which was also the highest a male Swedish player had ever been ranked, surpassing [[Jesper Parnevik]]'s previous record of reaching seventh place in May 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.owgr.com/news/fullstory.sps?iNewsid=406415&itype=&iCategoryID=0 |title=Henrik Stenson Wins the WGC-Accenture Math Play and Reaches World Number 5 |publisher=Official World Golf Ranking |date=26 February 2007 |accessdate=19 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120205103204/http://www.owgr.com/news/fullstory.sps?iNewsid=406415&itype=&iCategoryID=0 |archivedate=5 February 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> In all, Stenson spent [[List of male golfers who have been in the world top 10|over 100 weeks in the top 10]] of the rankings between 2007 and 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dps.endavadigital.net/owgr/doc/content/2007%20Stats/86TO0810.pdf |title=69 Players Who Have Reached The Top-10 In World Ranking |publisher=Official World Golf Ranking |accessdate=19 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |title=European Tour Official Guide 09 \n |url=http://www.europeantour.com/default.sps?pagegid={00387D2B-9D40-40B9-B2AC-C46939A8370B} \n |format=PDF \n |accessdate=16 January 2009 \n |edition=38th \n |year=2009 \n |publisher=[[PGA European Tour]] \n |chapter=Players who have reached the Top Ten in the Official World Golf Ranking since 1986 \n |page=558 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090116021539/http://www.europeantour.com/default.sps?pagegid=%7B00387D2B-9D40-40B9-B2AC-C46939A8370B%7D \n |archivedate=16 January 2009 \n |df=dmy-all \n}}</ref> This victory put Stenson in the lead of the 2007 European Tour Order of Merit, but he failed to add to his success over the rest of the season and finished in fourth place.\n\nStenson made his [[Ryder Cup]] debut in 2006, and after getting a half-point in the foursomes against [[Stewart Cink]] and [[David Toms]] on the Friday, he holed the winning putt and ensured that Europe won the [[Ryder Cup]] for a third consecutive time when he beat [[Vaughn Taylor]] 4 & 3 in the Sunday singles. He played again in [[2008 Ryder Cup|2008]] at Valhalla, tallying a win, a loss and a draw in the foursomes. However he was not as fortunate as two years before, losing the singles on Sunday 3 & 2 to [[Kenny Perry]].\n\nIn March 2009 Stenson created a storm in the media after stripping to his underwear and golf glove in order to play a recovery shot from a muddy water hazard at the first round of the [[WGC-CA Championship]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/14/sports/golf/14golf.html?ref=golf |title=A Revealing Shot Seen Round the World |newspaper=The New York Times |first=Karen |last=Crouse |date=13 March 2009 |accessdate=19 November 2013}}</ref> On 10 May 2009, Stenson won [[The Players Championship]] with a dominating final round score of 66 to finish four ahead of [[Ian Poulter]]. The win was his first American [[stroke play]] victory. This win again brought him to fifth in the [[Official World Golf Ranking]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.owgr.com/NEWS/fullstory.sps?iNewsid=6632334&itype=421 |title=Week 19 \u2013 Henrik Stenson Wins The Players Championship and Climbs to World Number Five |publisher=Official World Golf Ranking |date=10 May 2009 |accessdate=19 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110526205837/http://www.owgr.com/NEWS/fullstory.sps?iNewsid=6632334&itype=421 |archivedate=26 May 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> The following week he moved up to fourth without playing. Stenson faltered after reaching a career OWGR high. He struggled during most of the 2011 season, when he made 9 of 15 cuts but had no top-10 finishes. His world ranking fell to 230 at the beginning of 2012.\n\nOn 5 April 2012, Stenson led during the first round of the [[2012 Masters Tournament|Masters Tournament]] with two eagles on the front nine to lead at 6-under-par until the 18th hole. He scored a quadruple-bogey on the par-4 18th hole, tying the Masters' record for the highest score ever on that hole.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/04/05/henrik-stenson-masters-quadruple-bogey-18_n_1406711.html#s847024&title=ESPN_Stats_ |title=Masters 2012: Henrik Stenson Squanders Lead At Augusta With Quadruple Bogey |work=Huffington Post |first=Nancy |last=Armour |date=5 April 2012 |accessdate=19 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120630134640/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/04/05/henrik-stenson-masters-quadruple-bogey-18_n_1406711.html |archivedate=30 June 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n===2013===\n[[File:Henrik Stenson och Jerringpriset 2013-3.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Stenson won the [[Jerring Award]] for his performance in the 2013 season.]]\nIn 2013, a resurgent Stenson had a watershed season, scoring a number of victories and high-place finishes while cementing a reputation as one of golf's best ball-strikers.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Fulton |first1=Travis |title=Trips from Travis: Stenson's ball-striking |url=http://www.pgatour.com/tourreport/2013/09/24/fulton-stenson-ball-striking.html |publisher=PGA Tour |accessdate=20 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Baynham |first1=Wade |title=Henrik Stenson Swing Analysis |url=http://www.threeguysgolfblog.com/henrik-stenson-rocco-ballard-swing-tours/ |website=threeguysgolfblog.com |accessdate=20 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Cumberland |first1=Baird |title=A Sorenstam '80s Throwback? |url=http://jimmclean.com/default.aspx?tabid=1429&ArticleId=328 |website=jimmcclean.com |accessdate=20 August 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140821084241/http://jimmclean.com/default.aspx?tabid=1429&ArticleId=328 |archivedate=21 August 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref> In the [[2013 Open Championship]] at [[Muirfield]], Stenson finished as the runner-up, three strokes behind [[Phil Mickelson]], with a total of 284 (E) for the tournament. He shot a final round of 70 and held the lead for brief moments during the round, but was beaten by Mickelson's four birdie finish. This was Stenson's best performance in a [[major championship]], bettering his two previous T3 finishes at the same championship. Stenson moved back inside the world's top 20 with this result. Stenson finished runner-up again the following month at the [[WGC-Bridgestone Invitational]] behind [[Tiger Woods]]. He moved up to 11th in the world rankings after that result.\n\nIn the year's next major championship, the [[2013 PGA Championship]], Stenson contended again on Sunday, teeing off in the penultimate group two strokes behind the leader [[Jim Furyk]]. Despite an eagle on the par-5 fourth hole that moved him to within one stroke of the leaders, Stenson was never quite able to build any momentum in an even-par round that included four bogeys. He finished alone in third place, three strokes behind the champion [[Jason Dufner]]. Stenson moved up one place in the world rankings to move back inside the world's top ten.\n\nStenson's good form continued into the [[2013 FedEx Cup Playoffs]], when he won the [[Deutsche Bank Championship]] by two strokes over runner-up, [[Steve Stricker]]. It was the Swede's first PGA Tour victory in over three years. He tied the tournament record of \u221222 en route to his third career PGA Tour win.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pgatour.com/daily-wrapup/2013/09/02/deutschebank4.html |title=Daily Wrap-up: Deutsche Bank Championship, Round 4 |publisher=PGA Tour |date=2 September 2013 |accessdate=19 November 2013}}</ref> The win vaulted him into first place in the [[FedEx Cup]] standings just ahead of [[Tiger Woods]].\n\nOn 22 September 2013, Stenson won [[The Tour Championship]] at [[East Lake Golf Club]] and the [[FedEx Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://espn.go.com/golf/story/_/id/9707991/fedex-cup-playoffs-payoff-henrik-stenson-tour-championship-golf |first=Bob |last=Harig |title=Playoffs a payoff for Henrik Stenson |work=[[ESPN]] |date=22 September 2013 |accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref> He also tied his career best OWGR ranking of 4th.\n\nHe then moved up to a career best 3rd in the OWGR ranking on 3 November 2013.<ref name=OWGR-w44-2013>{{cite web |url=http://dps.endavadigital.net/owgr/doc/content/archive/2013/owgr44f2013.pdf |title=Official World Golf Ranking for Week 44 |date=3 November 2013 |accessdate=19 November 2013}}</ref> He finished the 2013 season ranked first on the PGA Tour in greens in regulation, first in ball striking, second among money leaders, third in total driving, fourth in scoring average, and seventh in driving accuracy percentage.<ref name=pga/>\n\nOn 17 November 2013, he won the [[DP World Tour Championship, Dubai]] with a record-breaking performance (an aggregate 263 score at 25-under par), thereby also winning the [[Race to Dubai]] which he was already leading. Having already won the [[FedEx Cup]] Series in September, he thus became the first player to win the FedEx Cup on the PGA Tour and the European Tour's Race to Dubai, and to do so in the same season,<ref name=ET-Stenson01/><ref name=GulfNews01/> a \"historic double\".<ref name=ET-Stenson02/><ref name=OWGR-StensonNov2013/> Stenson described his feat as a \"double-double\" because in the process of winning these two seasonal points crowns, he also won the season finales of both tours (the [[Tour Championship]] and the [[DP World Tour Championship, Dubai]]).<ref name=TheNational01/> He was later named [[European Tour Golfer of the Year]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pgatour.com/tourreport/2013/12/17/stenson-named-europe-s-poy.html |title=Stenson named European Tour POY |publisher=PGA Tour |date=17 December 2013 |accessdate=17 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n===2014===\nIn May 2014, Stenson reached a career high ranking of number two in the world, trailing only [[Adam Scott (golfer)|Adam Scott]]. On the PGA Tour, Stenson achieved career-best finishes at the Masters (T14) and U.S. Open (T4) while tying a career-best finish at the PGA Championship (T3). In Europe he won for the second time the DP World Tour Championship in Dubai and recorded 2nd places at the [[Volvo World Match Play Championship]] and [[BMW International Open]], en route to a final 2nd place in the Race to Dubai, behind the winner [[Rory McIlroy]].\n\n=== 2015 ===\nIn 2015, Stenson did not win any professional tournaments but made the cut in all 16 PGA Tour events he entered. He scored four runner-up finishes, including three over the final month of the season.<ref name=pga/> He finished as the overall runner-up for the FedEx Cup.\n\nOn the European Tour he registered a runner-up finish at the BMW International Open, just as he did in 2014.\n\n=== 2016 ===\nAt the 2016 U.S. Open, on Saturday morning Stenson failed to show up at Oakmont to complete his second round, where he was going to miss the cut. The USGA said Stenson did not give a reason for his withdrawal, but he later confirmed on Twitter that he had \"minor neck and knee issues\".<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.bunkered.co.uk/golf-news/henrik-stenson-no-shows-on-saturday |title=Henrik Stenson \u2018no shows\u2019 on Saturday |date=18 June 2016 |magazine=bunkered |first=Martin |last=Inglis}}</ref>\n\nA week later, he became the fourth two-time winner of the [[BMW International Open]] and the first to win the event at two different locations (at the Golfclub M\u00fcnchen Eichenried in 2006; at the Golf Club Gut L\u00e4rchenhof in 2016). The 2016 win at the tournament marked his 10th career win on the European Tour.\n\nStenson won the [[2016 Open Championship]] at Royal Troon for his first major title. Before this win, he had achieved eight top 6-finishes in majors, without a win. He held the 54-hole lead going into the final round with a margin of one stroke over [[Phil Mickelson]]. The pair played together during the third round and finished it by being six and five shots ahead of the field respectively, setting up a final head-to-head duel on Sunday. Stenson shot a 63 in the final round to tie [[Johnny Miller]] for the best ever final round of a major winner. His overall score of 264 set a record for the lowest score in any major championship. Stenson finished three shots ahead of Mickelson and 14 shots ahead of third-place finisher [[J. B. Holmes]]. Stenson became the first male Swede to win a major.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://espn.go.com/golf/story/_/id/17094320/henrik-stenson-wins-open-championship-final-round-showdown-phil-mickelson |title=Henrik Stenson claims Open for first major title |work=ESPN |date=17 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn August, Stenson represented Sweden at the [[2016 Summer Olympics]], where he won the silver medal; entering the final hole of the competition he was level with the eventual winner [[Justin Rose]], but bogeyed the last hole while Rose made his birdie putt to win by two strokes.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/olympics/36689345 |title=Rio Olympics 2016: Justin Rose beats Henrik Stenson to Olympic gold in tense finale |date=14 August 2016 |work=BBC Sport |access-date=1 October 2016}}</ref> Had Stenson won, he would have claimed victories on all six continents on which golf is played, a feat Rose with the Olympic win, joined [[World Golf Hall of Fame|Hall of Fame]] members [[Gary Player]], [[David Graham (golfer)|David Graham]], [[Hale Irwin]] and [[Bernhard Langer]].\n\nStenson won an automatic selection for the [[2016 Ryder Cup]] at the [[Hazeltine National Golf Club]] in [[Chaska, Minnesota]]. In the competition he earned 2 points for Europe in 5 matches, winning the Friday fourball with [[Justin Rose]] by 5 and 4 against [[Jordan Spieth]] and [[Patrick Reed]], and his single match against Spieth by 3 and 2.\n\nIn November 2016, Stenson won the Race to Dubai for a second time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.svt.se/sport/golf/golf-nu-avgors-race-to-dubai/ |title=Stenson vann Europatouren |publisher=SVT Sport |language=Swedish |first=Johanna |last=Cedergren |date=20 November 2016 |accessdate=20 November 2016}}</ref> Stenson led the European Tour in scoring average (69.14) for the first time in his career in 2016,<ref>http://www.europeantour.com/europeantour/players/playerid=2090/statistics/cupkindid=1/season=2016/index.html/</ref> which he has declared his best overall year to date.<ref>http://edition.cnn.com/2016/11/21/golf/henrik-stenson-race-to-dubai-champion/</ref> In December, Stenson was named European Tour Golfer of the Year for the second time in his career.<ref>{{cite news |title=Henrik Stenson: Open champion named European Golfer of the Year |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/golf/38305658 |work=BBC Sport |date=13 December 2016 |accessdate=16 December 2016}}</ref> He was also named 2016 [[Swedish Golfer of the Year]], male and female. It was the fifth time he earned this award.\n\n=== 2017 ===\nIn August 2017, Stenson broke the aggregate scoring record at the [[Wyndham Championship]] (258), en route to winning the tournament by one stroke over [[Ollie Schniederjans]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.spokesman.com/stories/2017/aug/20/henrik-stenson-closed-with-64-to-win-at-wyndham/ |title=Henrik Stenson closed with 64 to win at Wyndham |newspaper=The Spokesman-Review |date=20 August 2017 |first=Joedy |last=Mccreary |agency=Associated Press}}</ref>\n\n=== 2018 ===\nAt the [[2018 Masters Tournament]], Stenson finished tied for fifth place after 4 even rounds of 69, 70, 70 and 70 with total score \u22129. This result meant that he has managed to finish in the top 5 at all four major championships in his career. He also finished tied for sixth at the U.S. Open. He did not win any tournaments in an otherwise up-and-down year in which he faced several nagging injuries. However, Stenson rebounded with one of the finest performances of his career at the [[2018 Ryder Cup]]. He went 3\u20130\u20130 in his matches to join [[Francesco Molinari]] as the only players in the combined 24-man field to finish the event undefeated and untied. In the Sunday singles matches of the event, Stenson defeated [[Bubba Watson]] 5 & 4 with six birdies and no bogey through fourteen holes, and tied [[Tony Finau]] with best score relative to par at 6-under.<ref>{{cite web |last=Wittry |first=Andy |title=Ryder Cup Scores: Tony Finau and Henrik Stenson had the Best Days Relative to par Sunday at Le Golf National |url=https://www.rydercup.com/news-media/usa/ryder-cup-scores-relative-par-sunday-singles |website=RyderCup.com |date=30 September 2018 |accessdate=1 October 2018}}</ref> Being plagued by elbow injury through 2018 season, Stenson underwent a minor procedure on his elbow, causing him to miss [[WGC-HSBC Champions]]. In 2018, he managed to lead the PGA Tour in both driving accuracy and greens in regulation. It was for the first time someone has led PGA Tour in both these stats since [[Calvin Peete]] did it for three straight seasons in 1981, 1982 and 1983.\n\n=== 2019 ===\nIn December 2019, Stenson won the [[Hero World Challenge]] by one stroke over [[Jon Rahm]]. It was his first tournament win in more than two years.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ferguson |first=Doug |title=Henrik Stenson delivers big moment to win in Bahamas |url=https://apnews.com/0d0d54d971e47781acb7031d0b46ecff |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=8 December 2019 |date=7 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nStenson married fellow Swede Emma L\u00f6fgren in [[Dubai]] ten years after meeting her at the [[University of South Carolina]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.playerwives.com/miscellaneous-sports/golf/henrik-stensons-wife-emma-lofgren |title=Henrik Stenson's wife Emma Lofgren |date=12 May 2013 |accessdate=19 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dubaidesertclassic.com/modules.php?op=modload&name=News&file=article&sid=332 |title=Just-married Stenson Eyes Dubai Desert Classic Title |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927185249/http://www.dubaidesertclassic.com/modules.php?op=modload&name=News&file=article&sid=332 |archivedate=27 September 2007 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> In July 2007, his wife gave birth to the couple's first child, a daughter named Lisa.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.sportinglife.com/golf/news/story_get.cgi?STORY_NAME=golf/07/07/03/GOLF_Casey.html |title=Casey Joins Dropouts |magazine=The Sporting Life |date=July 2007 |first=Mark |last=Garrod |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930043558/http://www.sportinglife.com/golf/news/story_get.cgi?STORY_NAME=golf%2F07%2F07%2F03%2FGOLF_Casey.html |archivedate=30 September 2007 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> In 2010, the couple had their second child, a son named Karl. They live in [[Lake Nona Golf & Country Club]] in [[Orlando, Florida]]. In 2014, Stenson announced that he had invested in [[PGA Sweden National]], his first venture in golf course ownership.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.golf.se/folja/nyheter/2014/11/stenson-ny-delagare-i-pga-sweden-national |title=Stenson g\u00e5r in som ny del\u00e4gare i PGA National |language=Swedish |date=29 November 2014 |accessdate=13 March 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150315124314/http://golf.se/Folja/Nyheter/2014/11/Stenson-ny-delagare-i-PGA-Sweden-National/ |archivedate=15 March 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==Amateur wins==\n*1996 Italian Open Amateur Championship<ref>[http://www.e-magin.se/paper/1pfc350j/popup/1? Internationella nationsm\u00e4sterskap] (in Swedish) ''Golf - Den Gr\u00f6na Sporten'' (Golf - The Green Sport) Swedish Golf Federation 100 Years, p. 209</ref>\n\n==Professional wins (21)==\n===PGA Tour wins (6)===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:95%;\"\n|- style=\"background:#eeeeee;\"\n|'''Legend'''\n|- style=\"background:#e5d1cb;\"\n|Major championships  (1)\n|-  style=\"background:#f2ecce;\"\n| Players Championship (1)\n|-style=\"background:#dfe2e9;\"\n|World Golf Championships (1)\n|- style=\"background:thistle;\"\n| FedEx Cup playoff events (2)\n|-\n|Other PGA Tour (1)\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:95%;\"\n!No.\n!Date\n!Tournament\n!Winning score\n!To par\n!Margin of<br>victory\n!Runner(s)-up\n|-style=\"background:#dfe2e9